    <text>
        <body>
            <div xml:lang="grec" type="edition" xml:space="preserve">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/> 
                    <expan><abbr>Θ</abbr><ex>εοῖς</ex></expan>
                    ∙ 
                    <expan><abbr>Κ</abbr><ex>αταχθονίοις</ex></expan>
                    <lb n="2"/>Σεργίῳ
                    <lb n="3"/>  Ἑστιαίῳ
                    <lb n="4"/><persName ref="#pe_ServiliusFabianus">Σερουιλίου
                    <lb n="5"/>Φαβιανοῦ</persName>
                    <lb n="6"/>  <objectName ref="#pe_consul">ὑπατικοῦ</objectName>
                    <lb n="7"/>φίλῳ ∙ καὶ ∙ ἰατρῷ
                    <lb n="8"/>  Οὐιψανία
                    <lb n="9"/>   Ὁστιλία
                    <lb n="10"/>  ἐποίησεν. 
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>To the g(ods); to the u(nderworld).
                    For Sergios Hestiaios, 
                    friend and physician 
                    of the <objectName ref="#pe_consul">consul</objectName> <persName ref="#pe_ServiliusFabianus">Seruilius Fabianus</persName>, 
                    Vipsania Hostilia 
                    made this.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p><persName ref="#pe_Servilius Fabianus">Marcus Servilius Fabianus Maximus</persName> is a known historical figure. He was <objectName ref="#pe_consul">suffect consul</objectName> in AD 158.
                    Notably, this funerary monumnet was made (or at least commissioned) by a woman, Vipsania Hostilia.
                </p>
            </div>
